Below is a **single‑file, header‑only** binding that you can drop into a C project.  
It

* hides all C++ details behind opaque types (`bs_iter_t` and `bs_block_t`);
* lets a C program register a callback that is invoked for **every** block;
* passes the block’s most useful fields (height, hash, timestamp, tx‑count) in a tiny C‑struct that lives only for the duration of the callback – no per‑block allocation, no virtual calls;
* allows the callback to stop the walk early by returning a non‑zero value;
* is written so the hot path is a straight‑line loop with a single indirect call – the overhead is essentially the cost of calling the user function.

The file can be used exactly like the popular “single‑file‑library” style of `stb_image.h`, `stb_truetype.h`, etc.  The public API is the part **outside** the `#ifdef BLOCKSCI_IMPLEMENTATION` guard; the implementation is compiled only once in one translation unit that defines `BLOCKSCI_IMPLEMENTATION`.

```c
/*=====================================================================
   blocksci_c.h  –  C binding for BlockSci (C++ blockchain iterator)

   Drop this file into your project.  In *one* .c/.cpp file do:

        #define BLOCKSCI_IMPLEMENTATION
        #include "blocksci_c.h"

   All other files just #include "blocksci_c.h" as usual.

   The binding is deliberately lightweight: the iterator walks the
   native BlockSci range, builds a tiny C struct on the stack for each
   block and calls the user‑supplied callback.  No heap allocation,
   no virtual dispatch, no extra copying.

   License: MIT (feel free to change)
=====================================================================*/

#ifndef BLOCKSCI_C_H
#define BLOCKSCI_C_H

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Public C API – this part is visible to every translation unit that
   includes the header.
---------------------------------------------------------------------*/

#ifdef __cplusplus
extern "C" {
#endif

/* Opaque handle to a BlockSci iterator.  The actual definition lives in the
   implementation section below. */
typedef struct bs_iter_t bs_iter_t;

/* Opaque handle that represents a single block while the callback runs.
   The struct is defined in the implementation section; the C user only
   sees a pointer to it. */
typedef struct bs_block_t bs_block_t;

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Callback signature.
   The callback receives a pointer to a read‑only bs_block_t that is
   valid only for the duration of the call.  Return 0 to keep iterating,
   any non‑zero value aborts the walk (the value is returned by the walk
   function to the caller).
---------------------------------------------------------------------*/
typedef int (*bs_block_callback_t)(const bs_block_t* block, void* user_data);

/* Create an iterator for a BlockSci data directory.
   Returns NULL on error (e.g. directory does not contain a valid chain). */
bs_iter_t* bs_iter_create(const char* chain_dir);

/* Destroy the iterator and release all resources. */
void bs_iter_destroy(bs_iter_t* iter);

/* (Optional) set the callback that will be used by bs_iter_foreach().
   You can also set the callback directly in bs_iter_foreach() – see
   the overload below.  The user_data pointer is passed unchanged to the
   callback each time it is invoked. */
void bs_iter_set_callback(bs_iter_t* iter,
                          bs_block_callback_t cb,
                          void* user_data);

/* Run the walk.  The callback that was previously set with
   bs_iter_set_callback() is used.
   Returns
      0 – the walk completed over the whole chain,
      1 – the callback asked to stop early,
     -1 – internal error (e.g. chain could not be opened).                */
int bs_iter_foreach(bs_iter_t* iter);

/* Variant that lets you supply a callback just for this call.
   The iterator’s stored callback (if any) is left untouched.               */
int bs_iter_foreach_with_cb(bs_iter_t* iter,
                            bs_block_callback_t cb,
                            void* user_data);

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Accessors – the fields are stored directly inside bs_block_t, but the
   C API does not expose the struct layout.  This keeps the implementation
   free to change without breaking binary compatibility.
---------------------------------------------------------------------*/
uint64_t bs_block_height(const bs_block_t* block);
const char* bs_block_hash(const bs_block_t* block);   /* 64‑char hex + NUL */
uint64_t bs_block_timestamp(const bs_block_t* block);
uint32_t bs_block_tx_count(const bs_block_t* block);

#ifdef __cplusplus
}
#endif

/*=====================================================================
   Implementation – compiled only once when BLOCKSCI_IMPLEMENTATION is
   defined.  All the heavy lifting (C++ includes, iterator logic, etc.)
   lives here.
=====================================================================*/

#ifdef BLOCKSCI_IMPLEMENTATION

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   We need the real BlockSci C++ headers.  Adjust the include path to
   match your installation.
---------------------------------------------------------------------*/
#include <blocksci/blocksci.hpp>   // <-- Main BlockSci header
#include <blocksci/chain/block.hpp>
#include <blocksci/chain/chain.hpp>
#include <string>
#include <cstring>   // memcpy, memset
#include <cstdint>
#include <cstdio>    // for debugging (optional)

extern "C" {

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Concrete definitions of the opaque structs.  They are deliberately
   tiny – the iterator only stores the C++ objects it needs and a cached
   callback pointer.
---------------------------------------------------------------------*/

struct bs_block_t {
    uint64_t height;          /* block height (0‑based) */
    char     hash[65];        /* hex string, NUL terminated (64 chars) */
    uint64_t timestamp;       /* Unix epoch seconds */
    uint32_t tx_count;        /* number of transactions in the block */
};

/* The iterator object holds the real BlockSci chain and the range we
   will walk.  It also caches the user callback and its user_data pointer
   so that the hot loop does not need to fetch them from a separate
   object each iteration. */
struct bs_iter_t {
    /* The Chain object owns all the on‑disk indexes.  It must outlive
       the iteration range. */
    blocksci::Chain chain;

    /* The range of blocks (a lightweight view).  We keep it as a
       member so we can reuse the same iterator for multiple calls. */
    blocksci::BlockIterator begin;
    blocksci::BlockIterator end;

    /* Cached callback – may be nullptr (in which case bs_iter_foreach()
       returns an error). */
    bs_block_callback_t cb = nullptr;
    void*               user_data = nullptr;

    /* Constructor – opens the chain and stores begin/end iterators. */
    explicit bs_iter_t(const std::string& dir)
        : chain(dir), begin(chain.blocks().begin()), end(chain.blocks().end())
    {}
};

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Helper: fill a bs_block_t from a blocksci::Block.  All fields are copied
   into the stack‑allocated struct that the callback receives – no heap
   allocation, no virtual calls.
---------------------------------------------------------------------*/
static inline void fill_c_block(const blocksci::Block& src, bs_block_t* dst)
{
    // height is 0‑based in BlockSci, we expose the same value.
    dst->height = src.height();

    // hash – BlockSci provides a 256‑bit hash as a std::array<uint8_t, 32>.
    // We convert it to a 64‑char hex string (plus NUL).
    static const char hexdigits[] = "0123456789abcdef";
    const auto& raw = src.hash();
    for (size_t i = 0; i < 32; ++i) {
        dst->hash[2*i]     = hexdigits[(raw[i] >> 4) & 0xF];
        dst->hash[2*i + 1] = hexdigits[ raw[i]       & 0xF];
    }
    dst->hash[64] = '\0';

    dst->timestamp = src.timestamp();
    dst->tx_count  = static_cast<uint32_t>(src.tx_count());
}

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Public API implementation
---------------------------------------------------------------------*/

bs_iter_t* bs_iter_create(const char* chain_dir)
{
    if (!chain_dir) return nullptr;
    try {
        return new bs_iter_t(std::string(chain_dir));
    } catch (const std::exception& e) {
        /* In a real library you might want to expose the error string.
           For the minimal binding we just return nullptr. */
        (void)e;
        return nullptr;
    }
}

void bs_iter_destroy(bs_iter_t* iter)
{
    delete iter;   // safe even if iter == nullptr
}

void bs_iter_set_callback(bs_iter_t* iter,
                          bs_block_callback_t cb,
                          void* user_data)
{
    if (!iter) return;
    iter->cb        = cb;
    iter->user_data = user_data;
}

/* Core walk – the hot path.  The loop is a plain while‑loop over the
   native C++ iterator, builds a stack struct and makes a single indirect
   call.  No heap allocation, no virtual dispatch, no extra copies. */
int bs_iter_foreach(bs_iter_t* iter)
{
    if (!iter || !iter->cb) return -1;          // mis‑use
    bs_block_t tmp;                             // lives on the stack

    for (auto it = iter->begin; it != iter->end; ++it) {
        fill_c_block(*it, &tmp);
        int rc = iter->cb(&tmp, iter->user_data);
        if (rc != 0) return 1;                  // user asked to stop
    }
    return 0;                                   // completed
}

/* Variant that lets the caller pass a temporary callback without mutating
   the iterator’s stored callback. */
int bs_iter_foreach_with_cb(bs_iter_t* iter,
                            bs_block_callback_t cb,
                            void* user_data)
{
    if (!iter || !cb) return -1;
    bs_block_t tmp;
    for (auto it = iter->begin; it != iter->end; ++it) {
        fill_c_block(*it, &tmp);
        int rc = cb(&tmp, user_data);
        if (rc != 0) return 1;
    }
    return 0;
}

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Accessors – trivial inline wrappers that read the fields of the
   bs_block_t struct.  Keeping them as functions (instead of exposing the
   struct layout) protects binary compatibility.
---------------------------------------------------------------------*/

uint64_t bs_block_height(const bs_block_t* block)
{
    return block ? block->height : 0;
}

const char* bs_block_hash(const bs_block_t* block)
{
    return block ? block->hash : nullptr;
}

uint64_t bs_block_timestamp(const bs_block_t* block)
{
    return block ? block->timestamp : 0;
}

uint32_t bs_block_tx_count(const bs_block_t* block)
{
    return block ? block->tx_count : 0;
}

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   End of extern "C"
---------------------------------------------------------------------*/
}   // extern "C"

#endif   // BLOCKSCI_IMPLEMENTATION

/*=====================================================================
   End of blocksci_c.h
=====================================================================*/
```

### How a C program uses the binding

```c
/* example.c ----------------------------------------------------------- */
#define BLOCKSCI_IMPLEMENTATION          /* define in exactly ONE .c file */
#include "blocksci_c.h"
#include <stdio.h>
#include <inttypes.h>

static int print_block(const bs_block_t* blk, void* ud)
{
    (void)ud;   /* we don’t need user data here */
    printf("height=%" PRIu64 "  hash=%s  ts=%" PRIu64 "  txs=%" PRIu32 "\n",
           bs_block_height(blk),
           bs_block_hash(blk),
           bs_block_timestamp(blk),
           bs_block_tx_count(blk));
    return 0;   /* keep walking */
}

int main(void)
{
    bs_iter_t* it = bs_iter_create("/path/to/blocksci/data");
    if (!it) {
        fprintf(stderr, "Failed to open BlockSci chain\n");
        return 1;
    }

    /* register the callback once (optional – you could also call the
       _with_cb variant directly) */
    bs_iter_set_callback(it, print_block, NULL);

    int rc = bs_iter_foreach(it);
    if (rc < 0)   fprintf(stderr, "Iteration error\n");
    else if (rc > 0) fprintf(stderr, "Iteration stopped early by callback\n");

    bs_iter_destroy(it);
    return 0;
}
```

Compile (example with g++):

```sh
g++ -O3 -std=c++17 -I/path/to/blocksci/include \
    example.c -lblocksci -o example
```

### Why this design is fast

| Aspect | What the code does | Why it matters for 800 M blocks |
|--------|-------------------|---------------------------------|
| **Callback cache** | `bs_iter_t` stores `cb` and `user_data` so the hot loop never dereferences another structure. | One indirect call per block – the cheapest possible user‑code hook. |
| **Stack‑allocated block struct** | `bs_block_t tmp;` lives on the stack; fields are filled by `memcpy`‑like code (`fill_c_block`). | No heap allocation, no destructor calls, no cache misses. |
| **Plain while loop** | `for (auto it = begin; it != end; ++it)` – compiled to a tight pointer‑advancing loop. | The compiler can fully optimise the iteration; BlockSci’s own iterator is already a lightweight view. |
| **Early‑exit support** | Callback return value is checked immediately; the loop breaks without extra work. | Allows user code to stop after e.g. finding a particular block without walking the rest. |
| **C‑only API** | All public symbols are `extern "C"` and use only POD types (`uint64_t`, `char*`). | No name‑mangling, easy to link from any C compiler, and ABI‑stable. |
| **No virtual dispatch** | The binding never calls a virtual method on a C++ base; it only uses the concrete `blocksci::Block` reference. | Removes the indirect‑call cost that would otherwise dominate the hot path. |

With the above header‑only file you get a **drop‑in C library** that lets users write idiomatic C callbacks while the underlying iteration stays fully native‑C++ and highly performant.
